
[1]drove

   DROVE, pret. of drive.

   DROVE, n.

   1. A collection of cattle driven; a number of animals, as oxen, sheep
   or swine, driven in a body. We speak of a herd of cattle, and a flock
   of sheep, when a number is collected; but properly a drove is a herd or
   flock driven. It is applicable to any species of brutes. Hence,

   2. Any collection of irrational animals, moving or driving forward; as
   a finny drove.

   3. A crowd of people in motion.

   Where droves, as at a city gate, may pass.

   4. A road for driving cattle. [English.]
